Back in the days Alfa was the proud and joy of italians.
You can ask every old men across the country, Alfa was truly an icon for anybody.
Unfortunately, nowdays Alfa is just part of that shitty holding that aim only to make money.
They cut the actual production line only to three cars, all with mechanical and electrical problems.
They constantly push on tv commercials proposing leasings on leasings, not putting any attentions to customer care.
I would like to mention that back in the DTM days, german leadership allowed Alfa to compete in the championship, thinking that Alfa would have failed, but they litterally kicked their kraut-asses, so DTM started to plot against Alfa to make them lose and help other german brands win.
Despite that, Alfa is a brand that deserve much more respect, but FCA don't give a shit about; my fear is that will close Alfa in about 5-7 years from now.

Btw, as always I love your videos man, you're a truly fanatic just like us!
Cheers from Italy! Love! ❤️❤️❤️

snippet.textDisplay:
great video. Let me add some notes missing: the symbols used by alpha romeo represent the haraldic symbols of two families which ruled over Milan from the beginning of the second millenium: first was Visconti family whose symbol was a dragon eating a Saracen, in honour of crusades victory which Milan army led by Visconti take part in. S.George cross comes from Sforza family who succeed to Visconti. They are both used for representing Milan.
The first car Alfa Romeo produced as unlimited series was Giulietta, before Giulia, and it already had a sport version with a v6 that was called Giulia: they promised to customers they would have produced a Giulia Sporty version but as its production was delayed the sold in the meanwhile a Giulietta with that engine and called it Giulia.
The last car in Italy we considered a REAL alfa was Alfa 75 which it wasn't even mentioned here and it was made when Alfa was still a government property. Two versions of it were sold in USA and one of those was called America, mounting a 3.0L v6 with 188 hp.
https://it.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alfa_Romeo_75
The main difference with the following fiat production was the rear wheels drive, which is considered distinctive of sportiness. Fiat changed all its production into front wheel drive until Marchionne started Giorgio platform project, the paltform used for Giulia and Stelvio.
Alfa 8c was a beautiful car but it's frame body, by an idiot decision, was not designed to give the best performance as it shouldn't compete with Maserati.
One interesting cultural note: another important model produced from'70 s to early '80s Alfetta which for its characteristics was adpted both by police and from criminals in armed robberies and mafia assassination attacks.
